1806-2014 1975-2000 The Mick Moloney Irish-American and Popular Culture Papers are a subcollection of the Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Collection consisting of papers acquired and produced in the course of Moloney's career as a folklorist, producer, musician, and academic. The papers include research, administrative, and personal files; materials related to song and music collection; concert posters, programs, and other memorabilia; and photographs related to all aspects of Moloney's professional life.
Related Material at the Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives
The Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection is composed of five parts. Taken together, they illustrate Dr. Moloney's career long engagement with Irish-American culture across a wide variety of media with a particular focus on Irish and Irish-American music.

Historical/Biographical Note
Dr. Mick Moloney (1944-) is a musician, folklorist, and Global Distinguished Professor of Music and Irish Studies at New York University. He immigrated to the United States in 1973, earning a Ph.D. in folklore and folklife from the University of Pennsylvania. He has recorded and produced over forty albums of traditional music, acted as advisor for scores of festivals and concerts, and served as artistic director for the musical ensemble The Green Fields of America. In 1999, Moloney was awarded the National Heritage Award of the National Endowment of the Arts, the highest official honor of traditional artist can receive in the United States.
Moloney is the author of Far from the Shamrock Shore (2002) and numerous essays on Irish music and musical culture, and the co-editor of Close to the Floor: Irish Dance from the Boreen to Broadway (2009).

Custodial History Note
New York University's Division of Libraries, in conjunction with Glucksman Ireland House at New York University, purchased the Mick Moloney Collection for the Archives of Irish America in 2006. Until the Collection was transferred to New York University, under the supervision of Dr. Michael Nash, Head of the Tamiment Library, the materials were stored in Dr. Moloney's house in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. The accession numbers associated with this collection are 2006.071 and 2010.019.
http://mickmoloney.com/index.html was initially selected by curators and captured through the use of The California Digital Library's Web Archiving Service in 2014 as part of the Arts and Cultural Left Web Archive. n 2015, this website was migrated to Archive-It. Archive-It uses web crawling technology to capture websites at a scheduled time and displays only an archived copy, from the resulting WARC file, of the website. In 2019, http://mickmoloney.com/ was added to the web archive to replace http://mickmoloney.com/index.html. The accession number associated with this website is 2019.130.
Scope and Content Note
The Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Papers document Dr. Moloney's academic, professional, and performative interests and activities. This subcollection consists of research, administrative, and personal files; scholarly literature on folklore and ethnicity; materials related to song and music collecting; concert posters, programs, and other memorabilia; and photographs. The materials illustrate themes such as immigration and assimilation viewed through the lens of Irish-America's engagement with and expression of its own popular culture, with specific emphasis on its musical traditions. The time period most heavily documented in this subcollection (1975-2000) witnessed both a reinvestment by Irish-America in its cultural traditions and a transition of its musical traditions from the home to the stage, accompanied by unprecedented national recognition. The subcollection illustrates the shifts in policies regarding arts funding and programming; the valorization of ethnicity in the United States during the late 20th century; the rise in prominence of female performers of traditional music; and the Irish presence on and repertoire of the Philadelphia and New York music scenes.

Scope and Content Note
Series I: General, 1806-2011 consists of subject files concerning to Dr. Moloney's professional life as a performer, promoter, producer, and fieldworker. Materials include newsletters produced by various Irish-American "Celtic" Societies; scholarly journals on music and ethnicity; photocopies of early 20th century Irish-American newspapers; business and personal correspondence; an extensive collection (referred to as "Bookings") of contracts and correspondence detailing Dr. Moloney's performance engagements; files documenting behind-the-scenes studio work ("Recording Projects"); financial records and ephemera pertaining to major and independent labels, such as Green Linnet, Shanachie, Topic, and Transatlantic, with emphasis on marketing and the business models applied to Irish music starting in the 1970s. Of particular note is a complete run of the Shanachie label's newsletter and a collection of record catalogs dating back to the 1920s.
The series also contains materials concerning Dr. Moloney's involvement in numerous federally funded projects, including the Smithsonian Institution Festival of American Folklife (1976), the Chicago Ethnic Arts Project (1977), the Green Fields of America ensemble, the 1982 Knoxville's World's Fair, the International Village Fair in Philadelphia (1987), the Philadelphia Ceili Group Festival, and the Irish Week at the Augusta Heritage Center in Elkins, West Virginia. Scope and Content Note
Series II: Individuals, 1879-2010 consists of materials collected by Dr. Moloney throughout the course of his academic and professional activities concerning specific individuals and groups. The majority of these individuals and groups are Irish or Irish-American, are closely associated with Irish traditional music, and often performers. Others are Irish or Irish-American academics, poets, and writers, including the Philadelphia-based historian Dennis Clark. Scope and Content Note
Series VI: Photographs, circa 1930-2002 consists of slides, prints, and negatives of performers, events, and venues that appear in both the Papers and Field Recordings subcollections. Subjects with extensive coverage include Dr. Moloney's performing partnerships with Eugene O'Donnell, Robbie O'Connell, and Jimmy Keane; Moloney's package tours of Ireland and Scotland; the 1987 International Village Fair hosted by Philadelphia's International House; step dancing classes and competitions (some featuring Jean and Cara Butler); and slides prepared for Dr. Moloney's lectures. Of particular note are contact sheets documenting informal gathering of musicians and a 35 mm print of Did Your Mother Come From Ireland?, Dr. Moloney's 1981film on the Mulvihill School of Irish Music in the Bronx.Subseries A: Slides

Scope and Content Note
The website includes Mick Moloney's event and concert listings, yearly cultural tours in Ireland, his discography, reviews, and his writings.

New site crawls are accrued semiannually.
Appraisal
Crawl was limited to domains and subdomains of mickmoloney.com in order to remain within the collection scope and data constraints.
Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements
Due to technical or privacy issues, archived websites may not be exact copies of the original website at the time of the web crawl. Certain file types will not be captured dependent on how they are embedded in the site. Other parts of websites that the crawler has difficulty capturing includes Javascript, streaming content, database-driven content, and highly interactive content.
